                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15417426" author="busbey" created="Thu, 11 Aug 2016 15:27:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The mapred version already uses JobConf. Take a look at &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/hbase/blob/rel/1.2.2/hbase-server/src/main/java/org/apache/hadoop/hbase/mapred/TableMapReduceUtil.java&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;org.apache.hadoop.hbase.mapred.TableMapReduceUtil&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15417476" author="ngrigoriev@gmail.com" created="Thu, 11 Aug 2016 15:54:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I know but I always assumed &quot;mapred&quot; package is for old API and mapreduce is for new one. Thus, given the choice, I would go with new API for anything new. So with this improvement request I am challenging the move from JobConf (old API) to Job (new API). I was trying to search for the origin of that move but could not find any traces.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15417506" author="busbey" created="Thu, 11 Aug 2016 16:13:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Both the &lt;tt&gt;mapred&lt;/tt&gt; and &lt;tt&gt;mapreduce&lt;/tt&gt; APIs are supported upstream in Hadoop last I checked. We provide implementations for both, but in each we stick to the conventions of that API. In the &lt;tt&gt;mapreduce&lt;/tt&gt; API the &lt;tt&gt;Job&lt;/tt&gt; object is the submitters&apos; view of the submittal / configuration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If Oozie is only providing the mechanisms from the &lt;tt&gt;mapred&lt;/tt&gt; API, why not just stick with that? Or ask them to provide a &lt;tt&gt;mapreduce&lt;/tt&gt; oriented version?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15417577" author="ngrigoriev@gmail.com" created="Thu, 11 Aug 2016 16:53:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;OK, I think I see the point. I have just realized that other API classes in  mapreduce  package use Job. I agree with what you said about Oozie. Thanks.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
